title: Grateful Dead Live at Music Hall on 1973-11-30
description: Set 1 Morning Dew, Mexicali Blues, Dire Wolf, Beat It On Down The Line, Brown Eyed Women, Black Throated Wind, Don't Ease Me In, El Paso, They Love Each Other, Big River, Loser, Playin' In The Band Set 2 Bertha-> Promised Land, Row Jimmy, Jack Straw, Here Comes Sunshine, Weather Report Suite Prelude-> Weather Report Suite Part 1-> Let It Grow-> Dark Star Jam-> Eyes Of The World-> Sugar Magnolia This date is featured on Dick's Picks 14.

reviews.review_text: Definitions Mostly when the word "matrix" is used, it is incorrect.  This is a true matrix of the soundboard overlaid with the audience recording.  They are together, as one.  Incorrectly, it is a clean soundboard with intermittent AUD recording interruptions that often sound terrible, used to patch and splice missing sections of the SBD - not a true matrix.  This is by far the best matrix I have heard so far.  Nice job!
Here Comes Sunshine You Are The Eyes Of The World This is up there with February greatness. Doesn't really get better after Boston '73.

- One of the best sounding treatments of a recording ever. Extraordinary sound. I'm familiar with this show, but DP14 (which I own) sounds nowhere near as good as this MTX. The show is incredible, with an unbelievable 2nd set jam featuring my favorite Eyes ever.

Embarking on the no beard, no DJG tour And boy, what a first stop. Hard to ask for more in a Dead show than this 22 song monster. The Morning Dew opener is the first clue, the 19 minute Eyes is another. Great mix of newer material and old standards. And the sound on this particular recording is great. Don't own Dick's 14, and never will, because this show deserved it's own complete release, as I'm sure 12/2 does as well.

ONE FOR THE AGES I was only able to get a ticket for the last night of this legendary 3-night run.  This show, however, is an absolute epic performance with so many highlights.  The EYES is my absolute favorite,  Did get to meet Garcia as the band was staying at the Boston Sheraton and so were me and my group of merry prankster friends.  Unforgettable!

Dusborne Matrix -- You want it. Monster, sweet, show.  Five stars here.

Absolutely fabulous matrix by Dusborne.  Anytime I see anything by Dusborne, I know I want it.   He does a fabulous job.

Still laughing... Awesome set and great mix! 10 stars for all involved.

BY FAR, the absolute BEST Donnaskreech imitation by Bobby Weir at landing during Sugar Mag. LMAO

My soul beards witness Best lineup of the band here. No Mickey. Hey, he's cool and fun during Drums but he really messes up Bill's amazing jazz style. No Donna. And no beard. All great songs. Tight transitions. Good mix of crowd and band. Things got rocky with the disco 70s and a lot of the new 80s stuff was kind of bland, esp, Bobby's.  But this stuff right here is what I play for people not familiar with the band.  It is how you say kiss the chef. Starts mellow with MD and sets the tone for a chill show.

First use of “Alembic PA” a Wall of Sound prototype On this day in Dead history the band performed at Boston Music Hall in 1973 with the “Alembic PA,” a prototype for what later became the Wall of Sound. “Its on-stage speakers formed columns, saplings of the towering line arrays to come. Cobbled together with JBL speakers and ElectroVoice tweeters, all in Alembic cabs and driven by McIntosh amps, the “Alembic PA,” as this predecessor was known, had grown so large, Rick Turner said, that when it was loaded into the Music Hall there simply wasn’t enough room to put it in the usual left/stage right positions.”
